Purpose
The Control & Monitor Satellites form the external awareness layer of the RAMA system.
They provide tracking, navigation, monitoring, and safety oversight for the hub, factories, incoming regolith boxes, and all orbital traffic in the vicinity.

They are simple, rugged, and designed to operate autonomously for years.

Satellite Roles
Each satellite performs four core functions:

1. Position & Navigation
Tracks the RAMA Hub’s exact orbital position

Provides reference points for MOE navigation

Supplies timing and alignment data for factory operations

Maintains a stable coordinate frame for expansion modules

2. Object Tracking
Monitors incoming regolith boxes

Tracks debris, micro‑meteoroids, and nearby spacecraft

Alerts the hub to collision risks

Enables avoidance maneuvers if needed

3. Environmental Monitoring
Measures solar flux

Detects thermal conditions

Monitors radiation levels

Tracks shadow cycles and eclipse timing

4. Communications Relay
Extends hub‑to‑Earth communication coverage

Provides redundancy for high‑gain antennas

Maintains a mesh network for MOEs and factory systems

Constellation Layout
Three to six satellites in slightly offset orbits

Distributed to maintain full 360° coverage

Each satellite is identical for manufacturing simplicity

Designed to be replaced or expanded as RAMA grows

Design Philosophy
Simple: No complex propulsion; minimal moving parts

Autonomous: Runs on low‑power onboard logic

Redundant: Multiple satellites ensure no single point of failure

Serviceable: MOEs can capture and replace units if needed

Modular: Standardized bus, standardized mounts, standardized sensors

Power & Thermal
Solar panels sized for long‑term orbital operation

Passive radiators for thermal stability

Batteries sized for eclipse survival

Why This Matters
The Control & Monitor Satellites:

Keep RAMA safe

Keep RAMA aware

Keep RAMA connected

Enable precise factory and MOE operations

Provide the orbital “air traffic control” layer RAMA needs to grow

Without these satellites, RAMA would be flying blind.
With them, RAMA becomes a coordinated, intelligent orbital system.
